'''Tsumori Ōji''' is one of the {{ill|Kujūku Ōji|fr|Kujūkuōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=99 ōji Shrines|12=draft|12=draft}} on the [[Kumano Kodō]].
==Overview== {{Shrine | Name = Tsumori Ōji | image = [[File:Sumiyoshi Taisha Naioji Shrine (former Tsumori Ōji).JPG|240px|none|Former '''Tsumori Ōji''' within [[Sumiyoshi Taisha]] grounds.]] | location = [[Sumiyoshi Ward]], [[Osaka City]], Japan | coordinates = | deity = | Affiliation = {{ill|Kumano Kōdō|ja|熊野古道|1=Kumano Kodō|12=draft|12=draft}} - {{ill|Kumano Pilgrimage|ja|熊野信仰|1=Kumano Three Shrines|lt=Kumano faith|12=draft|12=draft}} | Established = | Map = }}
'''Tsumori Ōji''' (つもりおうじ) was the 6th of the {{ill|Kumano Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|12=draft|12=draft}} shrines, part of the historical pilgrimage routes leading to [[Kumano Sanzan]].
Originally located at the site of today's [[Sumie Elementary School]] in [[Sumiyoshi Ward]], [[Osaka City]], it no longer retains its original form. The shrine is believed to have been merged either with the {{ill|Shingū Shrine (Sumiyoshi Taisha)|ja|新宮社|12=draft|12=draft}}, a sub-shrine within the precincts of [[Sumiyoshi Taisha]], or with {{ill|Totoro Kibime Shrine|ja|止止呂支比賣命神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (also known as Wakamatsu Shrine) located at 1-10-4 Sawanocho, Sumiyoshi Ward.
The name "Tsumori" refers to the {{ill|Tsumori clan|ja|津守氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, an ancient family historically responsible for worship at Sumiyoshi Taisha and serving as its chief priests. Emperors and retired emperors on their {{ill|Kumano pilgrimage|ja|熊野御幸|12=draft|12=draft}} traditionally offered waka poems at this location.
== Access == * '''Sumie Elementary School / Sumiyoshi Taisha:''' Nearby station - [[Nankai Electric Railway]] {{ill|Nankai Main Line|ja|南海本線|12=draft|12=draft}}: [[Sumiyoshi Taisha Station]] * '''Totoro Kibime Shrine:''' Nearby station - Nankai Electric Railway {{ill|Koya Line|ja|南海高野線|12=draft|12=draft}}: [[Sawanocho Station]]
